{
  "texts": [
    "Several different, but isometric, models of hyperbolic geometry exist (Cannon et al., 1997).",
    "They differ in their coordinate representations of points and in their expressions for distances, geodesics, and other quantities.",
    "Although they can be isometrically mapped to each other, certain models may be preferred for a given task, for reasons of numerical efficiency, ease of visualization, or simplified calculations.",
    "The most commonly used models are the Poincaré model, the hyperboloid (or 'Lorentz') model, the Klein model, and the upper half-space model.",
    "• The Poincaré model represents d-dimensional hyperbolic space by the unit ball"
  ]
}